E. COLI EHEC - USA (03): (WISCONSIN), O157, RAW GROUND BEEF, ALERT, RECALL
**************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 15 Jan 2013
Source: USDA Food Safety and Inspection Service [edited]
http://www.fsis.usda.gov/News_&_Events/Recall_001_2013_Release/index.asp


Glenn's Market and Catering, a Watertown, WI establishment, is recalling approximately 2532 pounds of raw ground beef products that may be contaminated with _E. coli_ O157:H7, the U.S. Department of Agriculture's Food Safety and Inspection Service (FSIS) announced today [15 Jan 2013]. The products subject to recall are various sized packages of Glenn's Market ground round, ground chuck, and ground beef sold between 22 Dec 2012 and 4 Jan 2013. The products subject to recall were sold only at Glenn's Market and Catering in Watertown, WI from the retail meat case.

FSIS was notified of an investigation of _E. coli_ O157:H7 illnesses by the Wisconsin Division of Public Health on 10 Jan 2013. Working in conjunction with the Wisconsin Division of Public Health, 3 case-patients with the outbreak strain have been identified in the state with illness onset dates ranging from 29 Dec 2012 to 1 Jan 2013. Among the 3 case-patients with available information, all reported consuming raw ground round; 2 consumed product ground and purchased on 24 Dec 2012; the 3rd consumed product ground and purchased on 30 Dec 2012 prior to illness onset. FSIS is continuing to work with the Watertown Department of Public Health, the Wisconsin Division of Public Health, the Wisconsin Department of Agriculture, Trade and Consumer Protection, and the CDC on this investigation.

FSIS and the establishment are concerned that some product may be frozen and in shoppers' freezers. FSIS routinely conducts recall effectiveness checks to ensure that steps are taken to make certain that the product is no longer available to consumers. When available, the retail distribution list(s) will be posted on the FSIS website at: http://www.fsis.usda.gov/FSIS_Recalls/ Open_Federal_Cases/index.asp.

FSIS advises all consumers to safely prepare their raw meat products, including fresh and frozen, and only consume ground beef that has been cooked to a temperature of 160 F. The only way to confirm that ground beef is cooked to a temperature high enough to kill harmful bacteria is to use a food thermometer that measures internal temperature.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Undercooked ground beef is the prototypic vehicle for the transmission of enterohemorrhagic _E. coli_, responsible for the 1st recognized outbreak of the disease occurring in 1982 in the USA. Adequately cooking the beef together with good kitchen hygiene can prevent transmission. Needless to say, however, ingesting the raw ground beef maximizes the risk of transmission. - Mod.LL

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1hgE.]
